Transit Oriented Development and Higher Education Instituions in Mercer and Middlesex County

Higher education institutions have often developed in conjunction with cities. Tate (2008) shows the development of St. Louis and Houston, where highways were built through black communities to help transport white suburbanites to downtown in their cars facilitating white flight. Throughout this process, higher education institutions collaborated with policy makers and business leaders to ensure that their institutions would grow alongside these businesses to become elite schools. This shows the relationship that higher education has to development, but more importantly to modes of transportation. Dache-Gerbino (2016), used GIS and field notes to argue that black students did not have access to higher education institutions, because public transportation options were limited. The role that transportation plays to facilitate higher education are closely linked, and based on this relationship I chose educational attainment, Asian immigration, median household rent, and median household income as indicators to transit oriented development (TOD) in middlesex and mercer county’s NJtransit the northeast regional line.

Asian immigration was specifically selected to understand brain drain out of Asia. The idea of Brain drain is built on human capital theory—the better educated an person is the more productive they will be (Lauder, 2015). China has had a lot of talent leaving the country and as of the early 2000s China has made an effort to pull them back (Zweig & Wang, 2013). In the case that Asians are immigrating to Mercer and Middlesex county in New Jersey, I assume that they will be drawn to regional rail and more educational opportunities. The reason for the assumption behind their eagerness for educational opportunities, is based on US immigration policy focusing on highly skilled immigrants.The assumption being made here is that the amount of foreign Asian people moving into the Mercer and Middlesex county reflects enough of the whole population of the United States to be significant. In this case I am using Chinese and Asian very interchangeably, because in 2018 China replaced Mexico and makes up the third largest group in the United States. Additionally, I do not have access to specifically Chinese immigrant data and the census does not disaggregate the data.

Without going into depth on Asian American history, there are Asian Americans who have been in the US for generations, because their families escaped refugee crises, such as the Korean War or the Vietnam War. However, more recently, the United States has been focusing on skilled labor immigrants. These immigrants often have doctorate and/or professional degrees and the assumption is they would want the opportunity to be near higher education institutions and travel hubs. In the case they are unable to live near a large metropolitan city (such as myself), they would need to live near a regional rail line to access the city.

NJ Transit Northeast Regional line

For this analysis I selected regional rail as my form of public transit specifically looking at the NJTransit Northeast Corridor (NEC). The NEC runs from Trenton, New Jersey to New York City, New York.The reason I selected this area, is that I live in this area specified in the purple. I use the Princeton Junction station every Tuesday, Thursday, and Friday to get to campus using the Amtrak. Because I picked a regional rail line rather than a subway station, I needed to change some of the prompts. First, I changed the distance of the buffer for each transit station to 1 mile. This was because, unlike the city, there is a lot of distance in between each station (excluding Princeton and Princeton Junction). From my observations, most people will drive to the train station of choice, so the area around the station should be expanded to include the neighborhoods that are relatively close.

Total Population and Median Rent

The first maps shows the population of Mercer and Middlesex county in 2000 and 2009 shown through the size of the circles. The size of the circles indicate the amount of rent, larger circles indicate higher rents. The inflation in 2000 rent values has been accounted for median rent in 2019 is still higher, particularly in areas labeled as TOD. TOD areas were selected based on a 1 mile radius of the centroid from the station. The selection of the centroid would include the whole census tract that is included. The reason for this selection is because if residents were to use the regional rail, they would most likely use the one closest to their census tract. According to the two maps from 2000 and 2019 the median rent around TODS seemed to be much higher than in 2000 even when adjusting for inflation. This same analysis was conducted on total population. Total population is used to visualize the difference in population between 2000 and 2019. The 2019 population shows that there is more people. It is unclear if this growth is consistent with the rest of the United States or is unique to Mercer and Middlesex county Based on these two maps it is difficult to evaluate whether individuals have been more inclined to move into areas where there is regional rail access.

Distance

Distance to train station can be an important factor. Distance was found using the multipleringbuffer argument. Rather then use 1/2 mile increments, I chose to use a larger distance and larger increments. This is to account for the distance between train stations and the spread of neighborhoods in the suburbs in comparison to urban centers.

Median Rent

I plotted 2000 median rent data and 2019 median rent data over time. As indicated from earlier, even when accounting for inflation the median rent in 2019 is more than in 2000. I also included a line of best fit using the geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE). This line does indicate that there is a decrease in median rent as census tracts are further from the train station.

Median Househould Income

In addition to plotting median rent, I thought it would be important to plot Median Household income because, individuals in a census tract should be pay the cost of rent. As such it would be important to know what the median household income is. In the case of ToD, the distances closest to train station should be the highest, to indicate its high land value. In 2000 prices near the train station were lower than that of living 10 miles away from the train station. However, in 2019 the median household income seemed to be more consistent within the first 10 miles. There may be other factors which drove the median household income of the distance to the regional rail. The line of best fit suggests that the slope of 2019 is steeper than that of 2000. This slope would indicate a more drastic decline in median household income, given distance from the train station.

TOD Indicators

The indicators I will be using are Asian Native, Asian Foreign, median rent, total population, median household income, and educational attainment on four levels.

According to Zweig & Wang (2013), in recent years, China has made an aggressive effort to bring back their citizens who study abroad. In the case that China has been making aggressive efforts to bring back their citizens, that means their citizens must also be wanting to stay in the United States. As stated earlier, the data that is pulled for native and foreign status is specific to Asians. However, due to the limitations of how the census data is organized, I am unable to disaggregate the data. This graph is consistent with the increase in total population, because there was also an increase in foreign and native born Asians in Middlesex and Mercer county. Indicating that the area near the train station is of interest to Asian populations regardless of status.

In regards to rent, the average cost of rent near TOD’s are lower that that of non-TOD’s. This can be interpreted as with low rent, the train station can serve those who lack a vehicle to travel, or the low rent means the land value is low, because there’s a train station and no one wants to live there.

Education is often developed in conjunction with urban centers; however, it is unclear what the relationship that higher education has with subruban development. With Suburban Transit Oriented development in mind, it would make sense that education attainment near transit may be beneficial to education attainment.

In the figure 7 below, I plotted education attainment, in TOD zones in 2000 and 2019. Between 2000 and 2019 there was a decrease in high school attainment, with an increase in some college, bachelor’s degree and professional and graduate degrees. Despite this general increase, TOD educational attainment appears to have decreased in all areas.

Universities in Middlesex and Mercer County

Based on literature of higher education and urban development, I had proposed that higher education institutions would benefit from TOD. Using MedianRent in the figure below, from 2000 to 2019 there is an increase in the value of property all around New Jersey. To thoroughly answer this question, buffers around the train track can be made to calculate the average median rent around the school compared to the train station and an area away from the train station. Currently with the given data, there does seem to be a visual increase in median rent of census tracts that are near train stations and higher education institutions. What is not clear, is if the increase in median rent in these census tracts are statistically significant from census tracts that do not have a school nearby. Additionally, the schools would also need to count how many train stations are nearby to as the amount of access a school has could shape access to the institution. Lastly, it is unclear whether TOD is specifically drawing students to the institutions for example; did a student select Princeton University over University of Pennsylvania because of the train station on Princeton’s campus?

Conclusion

Based on the indicators selected it is unclear what the benefits of TOD are to census tracts around train stations in Mercer and Middlesex county. Although based on median household income and rent, the assumption can be made that the value of property around the train stations increased, thus more wealthy people moved closer to the train station. Although this can be seen as a form of transit oriented development, this may not serve the populations who need public transportation most. One curious finding was that educational attainment actually decreased for TOD from 2000 to 2019. Although there were broad increases in education attainment beyond high school, all educational attainment for TOD areas were lower. At this point there is not enough information to understand why this is the case. Data on Asian immigration is also too broad to make any statements about brain drain or why these immigrants are arriving; however alongside total population Asian, foreign and domestic, population also increased.

As this assignment only asks that we find indicators, I hesitate to draw broad conclusions about the indicators included because indicators are a snapshot. Additionally in some cases such as Asian foreign or domestic born, the data is not collected in a way that would appropriately answer the question. Furthermore, specifically relating to higher education institutions, there is not enough data to answer what the connection between TOD and Higher education, if there is one. This data could be supplemented with data from higher education institutions to provide a more robust picture of college access and TOD.

Based on some of the limitations stated, the indicators that were selected are poor indicators. They are not broad enough to provide policy makers a story without needing sufficient context as to their selection. In regards to a research study, there is potential for the data selected to provide a starting point for a study; however, this data would need to be used in conjunction with other data sets and qualitative interviews.
